{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625915"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17045"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.11,0.04,0.46,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76992"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9735"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62498"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5253"},{"type":"tags","id":"5292"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23062"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76992"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) antagonists are biological agents used in the treatment of autoimmune conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of TNF-alpha antagonists?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks TNF-alpha receptor synthesis","Reduces TNF-alpha gene transcription","Increases TNF-alpha degradation","Binds and neutralises TNF-alpha","Stimulates anti-TNF-alpha antibody production"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETNF-alpha antagonists work by directly \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding and neutralising TNF-alpha\u003C/strong\u003E in the circulation and tissues. This prevents TNF-alpha from binding to its receptors and initiating inflammatory cascades.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of TNF-alpha antagonists include adalimumab, infliximab, and etanercept. These medications are effective in treating various autoimmune conditions where TNF-alpha plays a central role in driving inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks TNF-alpha receptor synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - These medications act directly on the cytokine rather than affecting receptor production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces TNF-alpha gene transcription\u003C/strong\u003E - These medications do not influence the genetic production of TNF-alpha\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases TNF-alpha degradation\u003C/strong\u003E - These medications neutralise TNF-alpha but do not enhance its breakdown pathways\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulates anti-TNF-alpha antibody production\u003C/strong\u003E - While some TNF antagonists are monoclonal antibodies, they do not stimulate the immune system to produce endogenous antibodies\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-alpha) is a pro-inflammatory cytokine that plays a key role in autoimmune diseases.","TNF-alpha antagonists work by binding to and neutralising TNF-alpha, preventing it from interacting with its receptors.","TNF-alpha antagonists are used to treat conditions like rheumatoid arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease, and psoriasis."],"references":["Chang J, Girgis L. Clinical use of anti-TNF-alpha biological agents--a guide for GPs. Aust Fam Physician. 2007;36(12):1035-1038.","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62498"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:02:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:04:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9735"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76992"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":